headline: Some economists cite a body of research suggesting that the program has benefited U.S. workers, and the U.S. economy, far more than it has hurt
summary: Changes to the H-1B system could help U.S. workers. But some economists say losing foreign talent could hurt innovation—and shift production overseas.

headline: China leaves benchmark lending rates unchanged as expected, despite Fed rate cut
summary: The People's Bank of China kept the one-year loan prime rate unchanged at 3.0% while the five-year LPR at 3.5%, respectively, according to a statement Monday.

headline: Stock Futures Edge Lower Ahead of New Week
summary: This week's economic data highlight will be the Bureau of Economic Analysis' personal consumption expenditures price index for August.

headline: U.S. stock futures flat after Friday's record highs, as ‘market has learned to thrive in ambiguity'
summary: U.S. stock-market futures were little changed on Sunday, after the three major indexes all closed at record highs on Friday.

headline: Fed Musical Chairs: Who Will Succeed Jerome Powell?
summary: Andrew Brenner discusses President Trump's maneuvering to pick the new Fed Chair after Powell's turn is done. He speculates that the calculus could change if Trump is successful at kicking Lisa Cook off the board, giving him more seats to fill.

headline: S&P 500: Confusion At The Fed, Euphoria On Wall Street (Technical Analysis)
summary: The S&P 500 (SPY) continues its bullish trend, breaking above 6600 and targeting 7000, with strong momentum across all timeframes. Minor dips remain buying opportunities, as long as SPY holds above 6508; a break below should signal a larger correction of 300-400 points.

headline: Fed cuts interest rates: Is it a good time to buy a home?
summary: The Federal Reserve lowered interest rates at the September FOMC meeting. We look at what this could mean for mortgage rates, the state of real estate, and if now is the right time to purchase a home.

headline: Schatz: SPX to $7K & Why the Fed is Fighting the Wrong Battle
summary: The Fed is fighting the wrong battle, Paul Schatz argues, saying that even though inflation is warmer right now, it's ultimately under control. In fact, he argues that the Fed is “always behind the curve,” discussing the rate cut path he sees ahead, and the one he thinks they should take.

headline: Now that the Fed has cut rates, investors can focus on what really matters for markets
summary: Wall Street analysts have been raising corporate earnings estimates all summer, while the outlook for economic growth has improved despite a slowdown in the labor market.
